Is there much difference between writing a test for an interface and 
writing a test for an abstract class?

For example, writing a test for Map and writing a test for 
AbstractMap... you write your test methods, and use the Template Method 
patternt to decorate your TestCase#setUp with your implementation.

I&#39;ve tested abstract classes and interfaces in this manner before, and 
rarely had few complaints.

Steve.

---
Stephen Smith, MEng (Wales).
http://www.stephen-smith.co.uk/

Andrew McDonagh wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Yes, its normally better to test Abstract classes through their deriving
&gt; classes. This way you are testing the real classes that are certain to be
&gt; used, whereas any method on an abstract base class is viable for over
&gt; riding.
&gt; 
&gt; If it turns out that you are writing the same tests for each of the derived
&gt; classes, because they only implement one or a small number of the abstract
&gt; base classes methods, and you feel like its an exercise in typing out
&gt; tests.... Then &#39;the code&#39; is telling you the design is wrong. Wrong, as
&gt; in, why use Inheritance if all the derived classes do is add a single extra
&gt; implementation detail. The cure for this is to &#39;Favour Delegation over
&gt; Inheritance&#39;.
&gt; 
&gt; What would the design look like if you used delegation to call those extra
&gt; classes instead of virtual polymorphic calls?
&gt; 
&gt; E.g. Inheritance
&gt; 
&gt; class Car {
&gt; abstract String getMake();
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; class BMW extends Car {
&gt; String getMake() {
&gt; returns &quot;BMW&quot;;
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; class Toyota extends Car
&gt; String getMake() {
&gt; returns &quot;Toyota&quot;;
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Q: Do we Test Each class or abstract base class
&gt; 
&gt; E.g. Delegation (Note using the String class as the class to delegate to -
&gt; but it could easily be one of your own classes)
&gt; 
&gt; class Car {
&gt; private String make;
&gt; 
&gt; Car(String aMake) {
&gt; make = aMake;
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; String getMake() {
&gt; return make;
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; class CarTest {
&gt; 
&gt; @Test
&gt; testMakeOfCars() {
&gt; Car bmw = new Car(&quot;BMW&quot;);
&gt; assertEquals(&quot;Wrong make!&quot;, &quot;BMW&quot;, bmw.getMake() );
&gt; 
&gt; Car toyota = new Car(&quot;Toyota&quot;);
&gt; assertEquals(&quot;Wrong make!&quot;, &quot;Toyota&quot;, toyota.getMake() );
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt; 
